segments.text: This is a bright, sunny morning, March 30, and I have the joy and honor of being in the breakfast area just north of Moody with Dr. N.A.
McNeil.
I'm going to chat with him about his memories as a student and then as one of the dedicated members of the A&M staff.
Dr. McNeil, try your, say a sentence or two and let's see your mics working.
Now then, I was born in Moody.
Okay, wait a minute.
That's enough.
Dr. McNeil, give us an autobiography of your days before you got to A&M.
Where did you grow up and your family and what all did you learn growing up and that sort of thing?
Well,
My daddy was a dedicated Republican because he was related very distantly to General Sam Houston.
And when Harding was elected, daddy expected to get the post office immediately.
But it didn't happen that way.
He rented our farm.
to a distant cousin of his, and we moved into Moody after spending seven months as a farm overseer for a large landowner.
After we moved to Moody, we still were not able to get into the post office until the last month of 19 and 22.
At that time,
as a 10, 12 year old boy, eight year old boy, I started working in the post office.
And daddy would sort the mail into six stacks.
And we had two stacks for local customers.
And I put up the mail on the front part of the office while the carriers came in and took care of their
various duties with the four stacks that he had prepared for them.
After I got through with working in the post office with Daddy, I went to school.
And for six months, they had to pay tuition for me because I was not quite old enough to go to school that year.
But after we
Got into the, after the election and while we were waiting for his appointment, I went to school at a rural school west of Moody at Haunted Hill.
We had one teacher.
And I suppose I started my teaching career there.
Because when I went to Moody to school, I learned to read in the first grade.
And when I got to Haunted Hill, the boys that was in the first grade with me had not been in school but maybe six weeks because they didn't start school till cotton picking was over.
And the teacher who said to me, look, you've already read all of these books.
You go over and listen to this other first grade teacher.
first grade student as he learns to read.
After I got back into the Moody School, I was interested at age 10 in 4-H club work.
And it was several years after we got into 4-H club work before we got a vocational agriculture teacher at Moody.
But I took part in that activity.
Sometime in the early fall of 1930, one of my cousins came to me and said, look, you've just been in high school three years, but you've got as many credits in high school as I have.
Let's go to A&M together next year.
We'd been in 4-H together.
So I said, well, all right.
And we went down to A&M in April to the judging contest.
We were dairy cattle judges, and we didn't place in the contest down there.
But I went to the poultry farm and made application for a job.
And soon after I got home, I was told that I could work on the poultry farm.
In the meantime, I went down there and went to work on the poultry farm, but this cousin of mine could not finance in any way his going to A&M.
He didn't have a job, and so he worked for Daddy in the post office for one year to get funds to go to A&M with me the next year.
And Elsie and I went to A&M as part of the first project house that was ever organized at Texas A&M.
Now, this was the fall of?
No, fall of 32.
In the meantime, there's other boys from Moody who wanted to go to A&M.
And I came home and suggested that
if we wanted to go to A&M that we organize a group and go down to A&M and get permission to have a group from Moody who lived off of the campus.
And we went to see the Deans.
And Dean Kyle was immediately in favor of the project for the boys to bring food from home and rent a house and live together.
And Dean Winkler,
who at that time was dean of the College of Education, knew my father through the association of being postmaster at Moody and his family there.
So he said, look, this is great, we'll do it.
When we went to see the other two deans, Dean Friley, and I don't instantly recall, I don't know the name of the other deans,
We went to see Dean Francis.
Of course, he was completely deaf at that time.
And Dean Francis threw up his hands and says, whatever the rest of them decide, I'll go along with them.
Thank you for coming.
Two or three days later, we got a letter from Texas A&M addressed to my daddy saying that under two conditions,
that you can do what you have asked to do.
You must have someone to cook for you.
You can't do that and come down here and batch.
And the second condition was that you must have an A&M sponsor.
We have that requirement for everybody.
So Dan Russell, who made the talk,

at moody the year that year before we approached the idea was asked to be the sponsor for the group and he was very graciously accepted the responsibility and did a great deal of work to get the house organized he found the cheap old
house out near the Hort Farm that had been abandoned for 15 or 20 years.
Horse farm?
Hort.
Horticulture farm.
Oh, horticulture farm.
He was called the Suber House.
And it was ideally fitted to be a project house.
There were four bedrooms upstairs.
two bread rooms downstairs.
They had a parlor, a kitchen, and a dining room.
But they didn't have any water.
And of course, they didn't have any bath facilities.
So the parents of the boys, after we went down there, went down to A&M and replaced broken window lights, broken
whatever they needed.
And a well was dug by the landlord.
And it was cased with pine casing.
And you can imagine what that water tasted like when we had to make our meals with pine tasting water.
But we piped the water into the bathroom and into the kitchen.
And we lived in this house for 18 months.
The first house was very, the first year was very successful.
Who was the cook?
Lena McMahon, M-C-M-A-H-A-N. McMahon sometimes it's called.
Where did you all locate her?
Well, she was a cousin of both A.A. McNeil and Ethel Aiken.
mothers that went to A&M at the time that it was approved were on the steering committee that went to A&M.
And she was a lovely person.
And her husband came with her.
He was unemployed at the time.
And the first year, in August, when most of the students had gone home, Mr. McMahon was killed.
on the road down to the horticulture farm.
He was changing a tire on a truck and was killed.
And after his death, then Cousin Lena wouldn't stay with us.
We had to get someone else.
And the next cook and caretaker was unhappy at A&M and said on the first of,

january we're going back home to moody so that was the end off and by that time other project houses had been established and when those other houses were established most of the group went into the lufkin house and some of them went to the dormitory some of them went to independent but they scattered and the majority went to the lufkin house
Do you remember what you and others brought from home in the way of food?
We brought cured meat.
We brought canned goods, home canned goods.
And mostly it was canned, there was some canned meat that farmers had, the brothers had canned meat.
But it was, we also purchased our necessary items
from a local chain store.
And Dan Russell was instrumental in locating this red and white store that gave us a nice discount.
And we bought all of the necessary things other than that which we brought from home.
One boy brought a cow.
Every boy brought four hens.
We had a chicken pen for all the eggs we needed.
And we had all the milk that we needed from the cow that we brought from Moody.
At the end of June, that was the second, third year, my third year in college.
I had to go to summer camp.
Cut it off just a minute.
Complete.
It's on now.
Okay.
After I had finished my junior year at A&M, I was able to get a contract.
And with a contract,
In military science, I got $31 a month.
And after I got the $31 a month, I had to go to San Antonio for junior.
Between my junior and senior year, I went to ROTC camp in San Antonio.
I went to Camp Bullies.
And we had to work from very early in the morning until noon, and then they dismissed us.
And most of the A&M boys headed for San Antonio.
And there were only three or four of us that were there in the afternoon because we didn't have any contacts and we didn't have any money and we stayed there.
But in the meantime, I lost my contract if I did not take English.
So I went to Tarleton to get the only school that I could find that offered English that I needed.
And I enrolled in Tarleton, and the teacher in English was Pearl Mahan.
And she saw three new students in her class, and she said, Ms. So-and-so, where did you take your English?
And the student said, I took it at North Texas State.
And Ms. Mahan said, what did you make?
She said, I made an A.
She said, if you work real hard, you can make a B here.
And then she asked the second student, where did you take your prior English?
And she said, I took it somewhere else.
I don't remember.
And then she said, Mr. McNeil, where did you take your prior English?
And I said, Texas A&M.
She said, Mr. McNeil, didn't you know that this was the hardest, that my English course was the hardest in the state?
And I said, Ms. Mahan, I didn't know it till I got here.
But anyway, she had a peculiar system of grading.
I never understood it.
I never questioned it.
And I made a C, which would transfer to A&M.
And another rather peculiar incident happened out there.
Old Pop Hale had been teaching for years, and Pop Hale taught an education course, and so I enrolled in an education course.
And the first day of class, he asked a question.
It took me maybe decades of years to remember what question he asked.
But the question he had to do with the peculiar kind of monkey that was found on the island of Madagascar.
And when I answered that correctly, because I'd been reading the National Geographic, he called me Madagascar for the rest of the term.
And at the end of that class, he called me in and said, I want you to grade my papers.
And so in that
Six weeks I was there, I graded Pop Hale's homework for him.
I'd wait till the class was gone, get it, and then have it graded and ready for him to pass out the next day.
Now this is at Tarleton?
At Tarleton.
Did you by chance ever hear any discussion of a former student of theirs named Earl Rudder?
Not at all.
The first time I heard the name Earl Rudder,
had to do with wartime experiences.
I had my wartime experiences in a different area than Earl Rudder had his.
We'll get to those in a minute.
At A&M, as far as you can remember, what did it cost for you to go to A&M?
What was the tuition and fees when you were a freshman?
Do you remember?
For all?
That was for a semester.
Right.
And where did you acquire that $50?
Well, when my folks had to move away from the farm, I had a small dairy herd.
And when we left the farm, I had to dispose of the dairy cattle.
And I sent
a load of cattle to Fort Worth.
Eight head.
And when I got the check, after I had paid the travel expenses and so forth in Fort Worth, I had $85.
And I accumulated money from other ways until I had enough money to meet my expenses.
I had money saved.
that I used from various activities.
Now to take the tape off, I want to tell you something else.
Back to the project house.
Describe the routine of duties that you and the other young men had in that project house.
Who did what?
Each pair of boys in one room had to keep their room clean.

they had no other responsibility mrs mcmahan prepared the food they put it on the table and she did or her husband did the washing of the dishes in other project houses students were sometimes required to do part of the
dishwashers and so forth, but not in any that I ever lived in.
Did you all have any responsibilities for mowing the grass?
Well, yes we did.
One incident that we had, we had no sewer system.
We built a privy with a deep hole out there and one morning
when it got real cold, we looked out and there was smoke coming out of the privy.
And sure enough, Mrs. McMahon's husband was out there with a bucket of cold to keep himself morning while he did his morning's morning.
And one time, the rest of the boys got so annoyed with a couple of the boys that

they were not keeping their room like it ought to be and so they each got little sticks and they went in that room and completely dismantled everything going around with their sticks saying i'm killing rats we're killing rats in this room and they didn't have any trouble with those fellas not keeping their room clean after that how did you all do your laundry uh

we bundled all of our laundry up and took it down the road to a black woman who did the group the group laundry for everybody and it cost us maybe uh 50 cents a week to no more than 75 cents a week to get everybody's laundry done and they it was a very satisfactory laundry situation
In terms of food, it canned goods and cured meat, which would have been primarily pork?
Yes, pork.
Sometimes there was some canned meat from a beef animal.
In some families, they'd kill a beef on the farm, and they didn't have the frozen food facilities then, so they'd can the meat
that they couldn't cure.
What about dessert?
I really learned to do without dessert when we were in the project house.
Did anybody bring any syrup, molasses, ribbon cane syrup from home?
Not from this area.
And do you remember how much this lady was paid as the hostess
$1 per day.
$1 per day.
Well, $1 per month.
Per boy?
Per boy.
And there were how many?
There were 10 the first year and 12 the second.
So you lived there two years.
And in relation to the campus today, where was that house?
The first house was right across the street from the horticulture farm.
All right, but now.
On the F&B Road.
The Wellborn Road?
No, it was the road that was going towards Snook?
No, it was the road that went out by the dairy farm.
and the horticulture farm, and it was called F&B Road.
It was about a mile to the railroad crossing and another mile from the railroad crossing to the house.
How did you and your buddies get from the house to the campus for class?
Part of the time, we'd ride the truck that Mr. Mahan had.
It was a big old gravel truck, and we'd ride in the back of that.
Most of the time we'd walk up the railroad track and highway.
Very seldom did we have to walk all of the way to A&M.
At night, well, describe a typical weekday.
What time did y'all get up?
When did you go to class?
What'd you do for fun?
Well, we generally had breakfast at six o'clock in the morning.
And then that gave us two hours to get to an 8 o'clock class if we had to walk all the way, but we didn't.
We seldom walked all the way.
And at noon, we were able to get back for a noon meal and our evening meal.
We did not eat any meals away from there.
We had football games and various other activities.
that is confined to the 10 or 12 of us that were there.
Now you were in the Corps.
I was in the Corps and hated every day of it.
All right, did you have to be over there to fall in for?
The only time I went to the Corps was on drill day.
They lined the day dodgers up on the second floor.
And they beat the hell out of us.
My tail end was as black as your hat.
What did they use for paddles?
It looked like shaved down baseball bats.
It'd be as big around as a baseball bat, but it had flat ends.
And what outfit were you in?
I was in F company infantry.
Did it have a nickname?
Not that I know of, but it was made up of some of the better students at A&M that year.
I remember that one of the Astons was in that organization.
One of the Astons, from Brian?
No.
Who was that Aston?
Oh, Jimmy Aston from Dallas.
That's right.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Farmersville.
Right.
And...
Watson, the editor of the battalion, was in that unit.
There were five of us that were seniors in F Company.
And, of course, I was a second lieutenant because I hadn't been around all of the time.
As far as I know, I'm the only living person
that was in my senior class when I graduated.
The third year, see I stayed in project houses for three years.
Two years, because I'd stayed at the poultry farm one year and then project house two years.
And then in the Corps, I waited on tables at the mess hall.
And I was the only senior that waited on tables at A&M.
Most of the supervisors were juniors and been there for some time.
She'll get the phone.
Honey?
Now, you waited tables then in Sabisa?
Right.
My mama bought Lou Casey boots for me.
Cost $35.
And the seniors in my company decided I had not earned boots.
And they were in my closet.
And then they weren't.
And I had to go buy a pair of $4 or $5 lace-up boots my senior year.
And that's just... Did the Lucchese boots ever reappear?
No.
Oh, so somebody stole them.
That's right.
Somebody stole them, but they meant for me not to have senior boots as a day dodger.
Now, were all project house students considered day dodgers?
Until A&M built the 12 project houses, they were.
When were those built?
Was it after you were?
It was about 1937.
So after you were gone as a student.
About how many project houses were there before A&M built some?
At least 40.
Did you all call them project houses then?
Yes, sir.
Did you all refer to your first one as the Moody Project House?
We talked about it, but we also said Dr. Russell, D.R.
Russell, said,
had helped us, we put up a big sign, Russell Hall.
Describe him and personality and type and everything.
Well, Dr. Russell was a very compassionate man.
And he did just a fantastic work with all of the project houses.
but it was the Moody group that drew him into this.
And the year that I was married in 1939, the radio program that was called the Inside Story called him
when much publicity had been given to a Reader's Digest article saying that 2,000 people, 2,000 students were going to school on the co-op plan which originated at Texas A&M with Daniel Russell.
And he told them that he did not originate the plan, that I was a vocational agriculture teacher at Alvin,
And he recommended they get in touch with me.
And I got permission from the school board to go to Chicago.
And I was told that I would stay at the Palmer House.
And I thought that that was some little old side place.
And when I found out it was the biggest hotel in Chicago,
I went during the American Legion Convention, and they were dropping water in bags on people, and you couldn't get within four blocks of the hotel, and I had to dodge water bags to get to it.
When I came home, I told them that we couldn't get in World War II, and that was in 1939.
because we couldn't stand another crop of legionnaires.
Let's see, back to that first year.
Describe how you enrolled, signed up for your first classes that freshman year.
What did you take that freshman year and why?
Well, I took a regular course and I lived at the poultry farm.
And after the spring term, I won a dairy cattle judging for freshmen.
And I had been getting up before breakfast every morning and scraping the dropping boards from the houses and then going to breakfast and coming home and going to school.
And I worked on the poultry farm to make my payment.
I decided that after I won the dairy judging contest that I'd take dairy husbandry.
And that forced me to move from the poultry farm to some other arrangement.
And of course the project house really was patterned on the house where the students ate with the group of people eating at the hort farm.
And I think that the fact that it was patterned on that made Dean Kyle enthusiastic about it.
All right, as that freshman year, so you took math and English and whatever.
Do you remember some of those early teachers that were important to you later in your life?
Well, sort of.
but not my freshman year.
I had an English teacher by the name of Keyes, if I remember correctly.
Keyes, K-E-Y?
K-E-Y-S.
He had been an instructor at Thorpe Springs Christian College.
And the most person who influenced me most at A&M was A.D. Martin, a math instructor.
And he was, he
was a member of the Church of Christ.
And there was no building.
And he came every Sunday morning and brought the Lord's Supper for a devotional in the YMCA.
And on Sunday morning, I knew that I'd have a letter in the post office if I went to church.
My mama had a letter.
in the post office every Sunday morning.
And I got acquainted with A.D. Martin.
About how many attended that Church of Christ service?
Well, probably 15 or 20.
Were there other church groups meeting in the YMCA at various times?
As far as I know, not.
The Baptist Church had buildings just off of the campus.
And the first year that Brother Martin was there, he went down to Houston to explain the church work that he did with students at A&M.
And a woman by the name of Woodward told him that she wanted to build a church at A&M.
and for him to get plans for a church.
And when he got the plans and took it to her, it was a plan for a wooden building.
And she said, that doesn't suit me.
I want a brick building.
And she was the wife of a wealthy oil man.
And she says, I'll give you $10,000 a year for the next so and so.
And so
That building was built when I was a senior.
So that was the first?
That was the first building for the Church of Christ in College Station.
That's right.
And finished your senior year?
I was down there quite often looking at the building.
I watched them put every brick in it almost, but I was concerned.
And I really, I don't know how to go about this,
But Brother Martin gave me the cards for all of the people who said that they were members of the Church of Christ.
And I carried those cards and made those contacts of all of them.
And I knew by the time I was a senior, I knew nearly every one of the members of the Church of Christ.
Were there many members off campus or were almost all of them students?
There was only one person that ever came to that before church building.
One of the employees, the USDA, would occasionally come to that service.
And the others were students.
And he brought the message each Sunday.
That's right.
And then he'd go back to Bryan and go to church in Bryan.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Did you by chance meet Mr. Cashin, who was the YMCA director?
Oh, yes.
Describe him, please.
Well, he was just a fine individual, and he was compassionate, and he would do anything that he could for a student.
I knew all of the people that worked at the YMCA for a period of time, but I don't really have any
comment to make about him.
I knew him quite well.
Did you, in those days when you were living in the project houses, did you go into the A&M dormitories very often?
Only when they took me in there when I was a freshman.
I see.
I did not go into, when I had drill, I didn't go into the dormitories.
The only time I went into dormitories was to visit with members of the church.
What about some friendships that you made during those early years that lasted forever?
Who were some special fellow Aggies, special to you?
Well, now then, the people that was in that first project cast evidently were made up of different
background, and we've maintained contact.
And in 1992, we had been out from A&M over these long periods of years, and we had a reunion here at Moody.
And nine of the 18 who went to A&M in 1932, in the fall of 1932, met here at Moody for a reunion.
About how many of the original group graduated?
Half of them?
Two-thirds?
Oh, nearly all of them.
I don't remember but one or two that didn't make it.
We had one student from Moody that went down there and stayed a half a year nearly, and he couldn't make it.
But I don't remember anybody else dropping out, and I don't remember anybody else that didn't graduate.
When you went to and from Moody to College Station, how did you get there?
Highway did.
Road with them.
Describe some memories you have of hitchhiking to and from A&M.

Well, I can remember waiting on a corner in Marlin for 14 hours before a cotton truck came along loaded with cotton, and the driver told me I could sit on top of that cotton if I wanted to, and I did.
In the four years that I went to A&M, I went back to A&M on rail no more than twice when the weather was,
almost too bad to get if it wouldn't be anybody on the highway.
Where could you catch that train?
In Maryland?
No, I caught the train in Moody and went to Milano, caught a change of trains there and went to Valley Junction and changed trains there and got to College Station.
And I had two stops there.
changes in between.
Do you remember how much that cost?
No, I don't have an idea.
Did you ever have any bad experiences hitchhiking?
I wouldn't call it bad experience, but I got in a car one time that was loaded with rifles.
all kinds of artillery.
And the people in it identified themselves to me as Texas Rangers, and they were on the route looking for Bonnie and Clyde.
And I didn't, I got a ride and I was glad to do it, but the Texas Rangers picked me up one time, I remember.
Which way were they headed?
They were headed towards College Station.
They'd let me out at College Station.
Did you ever have any fun experience hitchhiking?
Interesting?
Goofy?
Well, at the end of my freshman year, I hitchhiked all over Central Texas, from Moody to Goldthwait to Hamilton to
back to moody and this spare country between the half of gold weight and hamilton i'll tell you that but i made it i had relatives living in mills county in comanche county
And when you hitchhiked, you always wore your uniform.
Yes, sir.
Did not put up a sign or anything like that.
Just rode your thumb.
That's right.
When you were going to class, how did you and your classmates, how did you all behave in A&M classes?
There wasn't any question we behaved.
And I want you to know that when I was an instructor at A&M,
I never had a student that was any problem in conduct.
My class was streaked one time.
I'm not gonna put this on the tape, but I'll give you my memoir that describes the incident.
If you and your buddies had some free time,

uh... where you didn't have to work or didn't have to study what did y'all do for fun for to relax i suspect we we there were two or three of us that that on sunday afternoon would go down into the woods and look for pecan trees and we found hickory nut trees down there most of us
Spent our afternoons, well, visiting and so forth.
I don't remember it.
Other than football, I don't remember that we played anything.
Any other game, we played football quite a lot when the weather was good.
Did y'all go to the movie much?
Not very often.
After walking to school and back,
Every day we didn't want to walk over there at night.
Did you, in Aggie lingo, did you all sack out in the afternoon?
Not really.
We either were going to school or working.
All right.
So you got up, ate breakfast, went to class, came back to eat lunch.
Right.
And then went back to the campus.
Right.
So you went to and from the campus every,
at least twice a day.
Right.
And we didn't walk over to the campus very often at night, I'll tell you that.
Did you study in your room?
Yes, sir.
Who had a radio in those days?
Nobody.
And by the way, we studied by Aladdin lamps.
There was no electricity.
What kind of stove did she have?
That's an interesting story.
We
Russell found some old stoves that had been used years before and stored somewhere.
And each room had a chimney in it.
And we had wood stoves in each room.
And sometime in the changeover from wood to coal down at the electric plant,
they had covered up a lot of wood that had been there for years.
And so we mined that wood from the covered up place at the back of the power plant.
Did she cook on a wood stove, though?
Yes, she did.
Oh, really?
Yes, sir.
Oh, my.
All right.
Did life change for you as a sophomore?
Was it different?
